statement:
\emph{Evaluate the following limit, if it exists.}

\begin{align*}\displaystyle
\lim_{x \to \pi^+} \frac{\sin x}{x-\pi}\end{align*}

sols:
Simply trying to evaluate the limit as written gives the following:

\begin{align*}\lim_{x \to \pi^+} \frac{\sin x}{x - \pi} = \frac{0}{0}\end{align*}

This is an indeterminate form and means that we can use L'Hopital's
Rule. Differentiating the numerator and denominator of the function, we
get the new limit:

\begin{align*}\lim_{x \to \pi^+} \frac{\cos x}{1} = \lim_{x \to \pi^+} \cos x\end{align*}

Simply evaluating this limit gives

\begin{align*}\lim_{x \to \pi^+} \cos x = -1\end{align*}

which is also the value of the original limit.
